, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Corbet was born in 0955, in Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France, his father, Hugh Fitzcorbet de Corbeau, was 10952 and his mother, Corbet, was 21. He married Giovanna Dei Carnaghi in 1019, in Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1020, in Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France, at the age of 65."},"et":{"0955–1020":"0955–1020","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0935–0955":"0935–0955","0935–Female":"0935–Surnud","1019":"1019","1004":"1004","before 1020":"enne 1020","after 0955":"pärast 0955","1020":"1020","0935":"0935","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","1081":"1081","1070":"1070","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"0955–1020":"0955–1020","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0935–0955":"0935–0955","0935–Female":"0935–Kuollut","1019":"1019","1004":"1004","before 1020":"ennen vuotta 1020","after 0955":"0955 jälkeen","1020":"1020","0935":"0935","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","1081":"1081","1070":"1070","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, Ranska","Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Normandie, Ranska","France":"Ranska","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Ranska"},"fr":{"0955–1020":"0955–1020","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0935–0955":"0935–0955","0935–Female":"0935–Décédée","1019":"1019","1004":"1004","before 1020":"avant 1020","after 0955":"après 0955","1020":"1020","0935":"0935","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","1081":"1081","1070":"1070","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, France","Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Normandie, France","France":"France","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Roger Corbet est né en 0955, à Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, France, son père, Hugh Fitzcorbet de Corbeau, avait 10952